  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <p><strong>How long does DBT take?</strong></p>
  <p>Standard DBT is typically a one-year commitment — long enough to complete all four skill modules and consolidate the learning. DBT-informed therapy or skills groups may be shorter.</p>
  <p><strong>Do I need a BPD diagnosis to do DBT?</strong></p>
  <p>No. DBT is used broadly for anyone dealing with significant emotional dysregulation, self-harm, relationship difficulties, or conditions like eating disorders and chronic depression. You don't need a BPD diagnosis.</p>
  <p><strong>Is DBT just for severe cases?</strong></p>
  <p>DBT was developed for severe presentations, but its skills are genuinely useful across the spectrum. Many people without significant pathology find the distress tolerance and interpersonal effectiveness skills transformative.</p>
  <p><strong>Can I do DBT skills training without a diagnosis?</strong></p>
  <p>Yes. DBT skills groups are often open to anyone who wants to develop emotional regulation skills — not just people in acute crisis.</p>
